04125nam a22005535i 9780226241050DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014043939  a9780226241050  a(DE-B1597)523213  a(OCoLC)904398380  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBF341b.P38 2015 4aBF341b.P38 2016 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a155.72231 aPaul, Robert A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMixed Messages :bCultural and Genetic Inheritance in the Constitution of Human Society /cRobert A. Paul. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Social Consequences of Dual Inheritance -- t1. A Brief History and Outline of Dual Inheritance Theory -- t2. When Genetic and Cultural Reproduction Diverge -- t3. The Cultural Channel -- t4. Two Kinds of Sociality -- t5. Society beyond the Genetic Program -- t6. The Asymmetry of Cultural versus Genetic Reproduction -- t7. The Society of Men -- t8. Symbolic Reproduction and Reproductive Symbolism -- t9. Beyond Gender Asymmetry and Male Privilege -- t10. Sources of Human Sociality -- tConclusion: The Giant Yams of Pohnpei -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs social and symbolic animals—animals with language and systems of signs—humans are informed by two different kinds of heritage, one biological, the other cultural. Scholars have tended to study our genetic and symbolic lineages separately, but in recent years some have begun to explore them together, offering a “dual inheritance theory.” In this book, Robert A. Paul offers an entirely new and original consideration of our dual inheritance to date, going deep inside an extensive ethnographic record to outline a fascinating relationship between our genetic codes and symbolic systems. Examining a wide array of cultures, Paul reveals how the inherent tensions between these two modes of transmission generate many of the features of human society, such as marriage rules, initiation rituals, gender asymmetry, and sexual symbolism. Exploring differences in the requirements, range, and agendas of genetic and symbolic reproduction, he shows that a properly conceived dual inheritance model does a better job of accounting for the distinctive character of actual human societies than either evolutionary or socio-cultural construction theories can do alone. Ultimately this book offers a powerful call for a synthesis of the traditions inspired by Darwin, Durkheim, and Freud—one that is critically necessary if we are to advance our understanding of human social life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBehavior genetics. 0aHeredity. 0aNature and nurture. 0aSociobiology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022624072540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226241050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226241050/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles